# The Router & RBAC Law

## FORBIDDEN ‚Äî Zero Tolerance

```ts
// ‚ùå FORBIDDEN: direct router.addRoute() in business logic
router.addRoute({ name: 'Dashboard', path: '/dashboard', component: Dashboard })

// ‚ùå FORBIDDEN: direct router.removeRoute()
router.removeRoute('Dashboard')

// ‚ùå FORBIDDEN: manual role checks for UI visibility
if (userStore.roles.includes('admin')) { /* ... */ }
```

## REQUIRED ‚Äî Canonical Patterns

### Rule 1 ‚Äî All Route Registration MUST use DynamicRouteManager
### Rule 2 ‚Äî Static Routes Live in `src/router/modules/*.ts`
### Rule 3 ‚Äî Navigation Helpers are MANDATORY
### Rule 4 ‚Äî Element-Level RBAC via `v-auth` Directive
### Rule 5 ‚Äî Programmatic Permission Checks via `useAuth()`
### Rule 6 ‚Äî Route Meta MUST be Complete

---

## Element-Level RBAC Patterns

```vue
<Button v-auth="['system:user:create']" label="New User" />
<Button v-auth="['system:user:edit']" label="Edit" />
<Button v-auth="['system:user:delete']" severity="danger" label="Delete" />
<Button v-auth="['system:role:edit', 'system:role:manage']" label="Manage Roles" />
```

### Table Row Actions (Common Pattern)

```vue
<DataTable :value="users">
  <Column header="Actions">
    <template #body="{ data }">
      <div class="row-start gap-xs">
        <Button v-auth="['system:user:edit']" icon="edit" text @click="editUser(data)" />
        <Button v-auth="['system:user:delete']" icon="delete" text severity="danger" @click="deleteUser(data.id)" />
      </div>
    </template>
  </Column>
</DataTable>
```

## Role vs Permission ‚Äî When to Use Which

| Scenario | Use |
|---|---|
| Coarse-grained feature section visibility | `hasRole('admin')` |
| Fine-grained button/action control | `hasAuth('module:resource:action')` |
| Template element hiding | `v-auth` |
| Script conditional logic | `useAuth().hasAuth()` |

## Wildcard Super-Admin

When user has `*:*:*`, all permission checks pass. This is handled centrally.

## Auth Bypass in Development ‚Äî `AUTH_ENABLED=false`

`VITE_AUTH_ENABLED=false` in `.env.development` bypasses auth checks for local development only. Never in production.

